SIMPLE: empale
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Empale
<hw>Em*pale"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Pref.
<ets>em-</ets> (L. <ets>in</ets>) + <ets>pale</ets>: cf. OF.
<ets>empalir</ets>.]</ety> <def>To make pale.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No bloodless malady <qex>empales</qex> their face.</q> <rj><qau>G.
Fletcher.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Empale</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Empale
<hw>Em*pale"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Empaled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Empaling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>empaler</ets> to
palisade, pierce, F. <ets>empaler</ets> to punish by empalement; pref.
<ets>em-</ets> (L. <ets>in</ets>) + OF. & F. <ets>pal</ets> a pale,
stake. See <er>Pale</er> a stake, and cf. <er>Impale</er>.]</ety>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>impale</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
fence or fortify with stakes; to surround with a line of stakes for
defense; to impale.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All that dwell near enemies <qex>empale</qex> villages, to save
themselves from surprise.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To inclose; to surround. See
<er>Impale</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To put to death by thrusting a sharpened stake
through the body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Impale</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Empalement</ent>⟦br⟧
